          <tr><td>$100,000</td><td>$833</td><td>$523</td><td>~$22,300</td><td>~$27,900</td></tr>
          <tr><td>$120,000</td><td>$1,000</td><td>$690</td><td>~$29,400</td><td>~$36,800</td></tr>
          <tr><td>$150,000</td><td>$1,250</td><td>$940</td><td>~$40,100</td><td>~$50,100</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The numbers may surprise you. At a $60,000 salary, the 20/4/10 rule suggests a maximum vehicle price of roughly $10,000 to $13,000. That is far less than what most dealerships will try to sell you, and it is also far less than what a lender will approve you for. But it is the amount that keeps your finances healthy and leaves room for savings, emergencies, and other financial goals.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What Lenders Look At</h2>
      <p>Understanding what lenders evaluate helps you see why their approval amount often exceeds what you should actually spend. Lenders focus on several key factors:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Credit score</strong> &mdash; Your credit score is the single biggest factor in the interest rate you receive. A score of 750 or above qualifies you for the best rates (currently around 4.5% to 5.5% for new cars). A score below 650 can push rates above 10%, dramatically increasing your monthly payment and total cost.</li>
        <li><strong>Debt-to-income ratio (DTI)</strong> &mdash; Lenders calculate your DTI by dividing your total monthly debt payments (including the proposed car payment) by your gross monthly income. Most auto lenders prefer a DTI below 45%, though some will approve loans with DTIs up to 50% or higher. Use a <a href="/financial-calculators/debt-to-income-calculator/">debt-to-income calculator</a> to check where you stand.</li>
        <li><strong>Employment and income stability</strong> &mdash; Lenders want to see steady employment and consistent income. Self-employed buyers or those with irregular income may need to provide additional documentation.</li>
        <li><strong>Loan-to-value ratio (LTV)</strong> &mdash; This is the loan amount compared to the vehicle's value. A lower LTV (larger down payment) reduces the lender's risk and can result in better rates.</li>
        <li><strong>Existing auto loans</strong> &mdash; If you already have a car loan, adding another one increases your DTI and can affect approval odds and rates.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The critical insight is that lenders approve you based on their risk, not your financial well-being. A lender may approve you for a $40,000 car loan even if the 20/4/10 rule says you should spend $20,000. Their job is to lend money profitably, not to ensure you can still save for retirement or handle an emergency expense.</p>
    </section>

    <AdUnit slot="blog-mid" format="horizontal" />

    <section>
      <h2>Common Mistakes That Lead to Overspending</h2>
      <p>Car buyers consistently make a handful of predictable mistakes that result in spending more than they can afford. Understanding these traps helps you avoid them.</p>

      <h3>Extending the Loan Term to Lower Payments</h3>
      <p>This is the most common and most expensive mistake. Stretching a loan from 48 months to 72 or 84 months reduces the monthly payment, making a more expensive car appear affordable. But it dramatically increases the total interest paid and keeps you in negative equity for years. On a $30,000 loan at 6% APR, moving from a 48-month term to a 72-month term adds roughly $2,800 in total interest and means you will owe more than the car is worth for the first 3 to 4 years of ownership.</p>

      <h3>Rolling Negative Equity Into a New Loan</h3>
      <p>If you trade in a car that you still owe more on than it is worth, the dealer will often roll that negative equity into your new car loan. You are now financing the new car plus the leftover balance from the old car. This creates an even deeper hole of negative equity on the new vehicle. Some buyers repeat this cycle multiple times, ending up $10,000 or more underwater on a depreciating asset.</p>

      <h3>Focusing Only on the Monthly Payment</h3>
      <p>Dealers love the question "What monthly payment are you looking for?" because it lets them manipulate the loan term, interest rate, down payment, and trade-in value independently to hit your target number. Always negotiate the total purchase price first, then figure out the financing. A $350 monthly payment sounds the same whether it is for 48 months or 84 months, but the total cost difference is massive.</p>

      <h3>Skipping the Down Payment</h3>
      <p>Zero-down financing is widely available, but it puts you in negative equity from the moment you drive off the lot. A new car loses 20% to 25% of its value in the first year. Without a down payment to offset that depreciation, you are upside down immediately. If you need to sell the car due to a job loss, accident, or life change, you will owe more than you can get for it.</p>

      <h3>Ignoring the Total Cost of Ownership</h3>
      <p>The purchase price is just the beginning. Insurance, fuel, maintenance, tires, registration, and potential repairs all add to your monthly transportation costs. A luxury vehicle or a high-performance SUV will cost significantly more to insure, fuel, and maintain than a midsize sedan, even if the purchase prices are similar.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Budgeting for Insurance and Maintenance</h2>
      <p>A realistic car budget must include insurance and maintenance costs, not just the loan payment. These ongoing expenses can vary dramatically based on the vehicle you choose.</p>

      <h3>Auto Insurance</h3>
      <p>Insurance premiums depend on the vehicle's value, safety rating, theft rate, repair costs, and your personal driving record. Full coverage on a $35,000 SUV typically costs $180 to $300 per month, while full coverage on a $15,000 sedan might cost $120 to $180 per month. Before committing to a specific vehicle, get insurance quotes for that exact make and model. A car that looks affordable based on the purchase price can become unaffordable when high insurance premiums are added to the equation.</p>

      <h3>Maintenance and Repairs</h3>
      <p>Budget at least 1% to 1.5% of the vehicle's value per year for maintenance and repairs. For a $25,000 car, that is $250 to $375 per year, or roughly $21 to $31 per month. This covers oil changes, tire rotations, brake pads, filters, and other routine maintenance. As the vehicle ages, expect these costs to increase. Luxury and European brands typically have higher maintenance costs due to more expensive parts and specialized service requirements.</p>

      <h3>Fuel Costs</h3>
      <p>Estimate your monthly fuel costs based on your expected annual mileage and the vehicle's fuel economy. If you drive 12,000 miles per year and the car gets 30 miles per gallon, you will use about 400 gallons per year. At $3.50 per gallon, that is $1,400 per year or about $117 per month. A vehicle that gets 20 MPG instead of 30 MPG increases that cost to $175 per month, adding $58 per month to your transportation budget.</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Expense Category</th>
            <th>Economy Sedan ($18K)</th>
            <th>Midsize SUV ($35K)</th>
            <th>Luxury Vehicle ($50K)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
