          <tr><td>Monthly car payment (48 mo, 20% down, 6%)</td><td>~$338</td><td>~$658</td><td>~$940</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Insurance (full coverage)</td><td>~$140</td><td>~$210</td><td>~$300</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Fuel (12K miles/yr)</td><td>~$110</td><td>~$155</td><td>~$175</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Maintenance (annual avg/mo)</td><td>~$15</td><td>~$30</td><td>~$50</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Total monthly cost</td><td>~$603</td><td>~$1,053</td><td>~$1,465</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Income needed (20/4/10 rule)</td><td>$72,400</td><td>$126,400</td><td>$175,800</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>This table illustrates why the 20/4/10 rule is so revealing. A $35,000 SUV requires a household income of roughly $126,000 to be truly affordable when all transportation costs are included. Many buyers earning $70,000 to $80,000 purchase vehicles in this range because the lender approves the loan, not realizing how much of their budget is consumed by total transportation costs.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>When to Buy Used Instead</h2>
      <p>If the 20/4/10 rule reveals that the new car you want is out of your budget, buying used is often the smarter financial move. Here is why:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Depreciation has already occurred.</strong> A 2 to 3-year-old vehicle has already absorbed the steepest depreciation hit (30% to 40% of its original value). You get a relatively new car at a significantly lower price, and the rate of future depreciation slows down.</li>
        <li><strong>Lower insurance premiums.</strong> Used cars are less expensive to insure because their replacement value is lower. This reduces one of the major components of your transportation budget.</li>
        <li><strong>More car for your budget.</strong> Instead of a base model new car at $25,000, you might afford a 3-year-old version of the next trim level up at the same price point, or a comparable vehicle for $15,000 to $18,000.</li>
        <li><strong>Easier to meet the 20% down payment.</strong> A 20% down payment on a $35,000 new car is $7,000. On a $18,000 used car, it is $3,600. The lower down payment requirement makes it easier to follow the 20/4/10 rule without draining your savings.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The sweet spot for used car value is typically 2 to 4 years old with 25,000 to 50,000 miles. These vehicles are past the worst depreciation but still have plenty of reliable life remaining. Many are still covered by the original manufacturer's powertrain warranty. Consider certified pre-owned (CPO) vehicles, which come with extended warranties and have passed manufacturer inspections.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Alternative Affordability Rules</h2>
      <p>The 20/4/10 rule is conservative by design. Some financial experts offer alternative guidelines that may better fit certain situations:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>The 15% rule</strong> &mdash; Some advisors suggest keeping total transportation costs at or below 15% of your take-home (net) pay rather than 10% of gross. This is slightly more permissive and uses net income, which better reflects what you actually have to spend.</li>
        <li><strong>The 35% rule (one-third of income)</strong> &mdash; This guideline suggests the total purchase price of your vehicle should not exceed 35% of your annual gross income. On a $80,000 salary, that caps you at a $28,000 vehicle. This is a simpler calculation but does not account for loan terms or total ownership costs.</li>
        <li><strong>The half-income rule</strong> &mdash; Some financial planners recommend that the total value of all your vehicles should not exceed half your annual household income. For a $100,000 household income, that means no more than $50,000 in total vehicle value, which could be one $50,000 car or two $25,000 cars.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Regardless of which rule you follow, the underlying principle is the same: do not let car expenses consume so much of your income that you cannot save for retirement, build an emergency fund, or cover unexpected expenses. Use a <a href="/automotive-calculators/car-payment-calculator/">car payment calculator</a> to model different scenarios and find the payment that works within your chosen framework.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Practical Steps Before You Buy</h2>
      <p>Before visiting a dealership or browsing online listings, take these steps to set yourself up for a smart purchase:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Calculate your budget using the 20/4/10 rule.</strong> Know your maximum vehicle price before you start shopping. Write this number down and commit to it.</li>
        <li><strong>Check your credit score.</strong> Your credit score determines the interest rate you will qualify for. If your score is below 700, consider waiting 3 to 6 months to improve it before buying. Even a 1% to 2% reduction in APR can save hundreds or thousands over the loan term.</li>
        <li><strong>Get pre-approved for financing.</strong> Visit your bank or credit union and get pre-approved for an auto loan before going to the dealership. This gives you a benchmark rate and puts you in a stronger negotiating position. Dealer financing may beat your pre-approval rate, but you should always have a backup option.</li>
        <li><strong>Get insurance quotes for specific vehicles.</strong> Before falling in love with a particular car, get insurance quotes for that make, model, and year. Some vehicles are disproportionately expensive to insure.</li>
        <li><strong>Research total cost of ownership.</strong> Look up the estimated 5-year cost of ownership for vehicles you are considering. Our <a href="/automotive-calculators/car-affordability-calculator/">car affordability calculator</a> can help you estimate the full picture.</li>
        <li><strong>Save your down payment first.</strong> Do not rush into a purchase before you have the 20% down payment saved. Financing without a sufficient down payment increases your risk and your costs.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is the 20/4/10 rule for buying a car?</h3>
      <p>The 20/4/10 rule recommends putting at least 20% down, financing for no more than 4 years (48 months), and keeping your total monthly transportation costs (car payment, insurance, and fuel) at or below 10% of your gross monthly income. Following this rule prevents negative equity, minimizes interest expense, and ensures your car does not consume too large a share of your income.</p>

      <h3>How much car can I afford on a $60,000 salary?</h3>
      <p>On a $60,000 annual salary, the 20/4/10 rule gives you a total monthly transportation budget of $500. After subtracting approximately $150 for insurance and $120 for fuel, you have about $230 for a car payment. With a 48-month loan at 6% APR and a 20% down payment, you could afford a car priced around $10,000 to $13,000. This may seem low, but it is the amount that keeps your overall finances healthy.</p>

      <h3>Should I include insurance and gas when calculating car affordability?</h3>
      <p>Yes, absolutely. The car payment alone does not represent your true transportation cost. Insurance premiums, fuel, maintenance, and registration are all recurring expenses that add up significantly. The 20/4/10 rule specifically includes insurance and fuel in the 10% calculation. Ignoring these costs is one of the most common reasons car buyers end up stretched beyond their budget.</p>
    </section>

